<div class="html-dynamic">

            
                        
        
        <section>
            <div class="art-abstract art-abstract-new in-tab hypothesis_container">
                                    <p>
                        <div><section class="html-abstract" id="html-abstract">
            <h2 id="html-abstract-title">Abstract</h2>
            <div class="html-p">In the 4th industrial era, the proliferation of interconnected smart devices and advancements in AI, particularly big data and machine learning, have integrated various industrial domains into cyberspace. This convergence brings novel security threats, making it essential to prevent known incidents and anticipate potential breaches. This study develops a scenario-based evaluation system to predict and evaluate possible security accidents using the MITRE ATT&amp;CK framework. It analyzes various security incidents, leveraging attack strategies and techniques to create detailed security scenarios and profiling services. Key contributions include integrating security logs, quantifying incident likelihood, and establishing proactive threat management measures. The study also proposes automated security audits and legacy system integration to enhance security posture. Experimental results show the system&rsquo;s efficacy in detecting and preventing threats, providing actionable insights and a structured approach to threat analysis and response. This research lays the foundation for advanced security prediction systems, ensuring robust defense mechanisms against emerging cyber threats.</div>
    </section>
    <div id="html-keywords">
        <div class="html-gwd-group"><div id="html-keywords-title">Keywords: </div><a href="/search?q=scenario-based+evaluation+system">scenario-based evaluation system</a>; <a href="/search?q=security+accident+prediction">security accident prediction</a>; <a href="/search?q=MITRE+ATT%26CK+framework">MITRE ATT&amp;CK framework</a>; <a href="/search?q=cyber+threat+management">cyber threat management</a>; <a href="/search?q=automated+security+audits">automated security audits</a></div>
      <div>
        
      </div>
    </div>
</div>

                    </p>
                            </div>

                    
    
            
            
    
        </section>
    </div>

    <div class="hypothesis_container">
        
    <ul class="menu html-nav" data-prev-node="#html-quick-links-title">
</ul>
<div class="html-body">
    <section  id='sec1-applsci-14-11836' type='intro'><h2 data-nested='1'>  1. Introduction</h2><div class='html-p'>The integration of advanced technologies such as artificial intelligence (AI), big data, and machine learning in the Fourth Industrial Revolution has led to significant advancements across various industries by seamlessly connecting them to cyberspace. However, this technological convergence has also introduced increasingly sophisticated cybersecurity threats. Existing security measures, including heuristic and signature-based detection methods, primarily operate reactively, addressing threats only after incidents occur. This reactive approach leaves organizations vulnerable to novel and evolving attack vectors, creating an urgent need for proactive and comprehensive threat management systems [<a href="#B1-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">1</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>This study aims to address these challenges by proposing a scenario-based security incident prediction system that leverages the MITRE ATT&amp;CK framework. The system integrates diverse security logs, simulates adversarial tactics and techniques, and quantifies the likelihood of potential security incidents. By automating the profiling of security incidents and enhancing predictive capabilities, the proposed system establishes a structured and proactive threat management framework [<a href="#B2-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">2</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>The contributions of this research are threefold. First, the study develops an automated framework for generating scenario-based security incident simulations, enabling detailed profiling of potential attack vectors. Second, it enhances predictive capabilities by integrating unstructured and structured security logs, allowing for a comprehensive analysis of security incidents. Third, the research introduces a novel methodology for seamlessly integrating legacy systems with modern threat intelligence platforms, thereby streamlining proactive security management.</div><div class='html-p'>By addressing the limitations of traditional detection-based security products, this research lays the groundwork for advanced security systems capable of mitigating emerging cyber threats. The findings provide actionable insights and robust defense mechanisms for organizations operating in increasingly complex and interconnected digital environments. This study not only contributes to the theoretical advancement of threat modeling and prediction but also offers practical solutions to improve organizational cybersecurity posture [<a href="#B3-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">3</a>].</div></section><section  id='sec2-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h2 data-nested='1'>  2. Related Work</h2><div class='html-p'>Recent studies on security incident prediction systems have increasingly leveraged frameworks such as MITRE ATT&amp;CK to enhance threat detection and response capabilities. Strom et al. (2018) utilized the ATT&amp;CK framework to identify defensive gaps and develop behavior-based analytic detection techniques through adversary emulation [<a href="#B4-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">4</a>] Similarly, Homer et al. (2013) explored the use of attack graphs to aggregate vulnerability metrics in enterprise networks, emphasizing systematic modeling of adversarial behaviors. However, these studies primarily rely on manual processes for scenario creation and analysis, limiting their scalability and real-time applicability [<a href="#B5-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">5</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>Traditional approaches to threat management often depend on tools like SIEM (Security Information and Event Management) and ESM (Enterprise Security Management). While SIEM excels at centralized management of structured log data, it struggles with processing unstructured or diverse data formats. Additionally, both SIEM and ESM are highly reliant on manual analysis by security personnel, which introduces bottlenecks in scalability and precision, especially for advanced threats such as APTs and ransomware. For instance, the 2021 KISA report highlighted that manual processes in SIEM systems hinder the timely correlation of security events and logs, reducing their effectiveness against rapidly evolving threats [<a href="#B6-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">6</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>Despite these advancements, limitations persist. Current frameworks often overlook the integration of unstructured data sources and fail to automate the generation of attack scenarios. Ahn et al. (2020) addressed this gap by incorporating automated adversary emulation, yet their methodology lacked comprehensive integration with legacy systems or the ability to process heterogeneous data formats [<a href="#B7-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">7</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>In contrast, this study aims to overcome these challenges by introducing a scenario-based security incident prediction system that integrates both structured and unstructured logs, automates the profiling of security scenarios, and bridges the gap between legacy systems and advanced threat modeling. Unlike traditional SIEM or ESM systems, the proposed framework leverages the predictive capabilities of the MITRE ATT&amp;CK framework while addressing their inherent limitations through automation and enhanced data integration. For example, this study addresses the weaknesses identified by Strom et al. by minimizing manual effort through automated scenario generation and real-time log analysis [<a href="#B8-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">8</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>Furthermore, while prior studies such as Kim et al. (2021) have analyzed vulnerabilities in specific industrial settings, they often lack a systematic approach to mapping adversarial tactics to actionable security measures. This research builds upon their findings by integrating scenario-based simulations to enhance proactive threat management and mitigate risks in dynamic environments.</div><div class='html-p'>By synthesizing the strengths and addressing the weaknesses of existing methodologies, this study contributes to the advancement of predictive cybersecurity frameworks.</div></section><section  id='sec3-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h2 data-nested='1'>  3. Existing Security Incidents and Limitations of Security Products</h2><section  id='sec3dot1-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h3 class='html-italic' data-nested='2'>  3.1. Cases of Security Threats in Korea and Abroad</h3><div class='html-p'>According to IBM’s 2023 report on data breach costs, based on a survey of more than 500 companies and organizations worldwide, the shift in work environments following the outbreak of COVID-19 has made it more challenging to control security incidents [<a href="#B9-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">9</a>]. The costs associated with preventing security breaches have also risen by over 10% compared to 2021. The average cost of a data breach has reached USD 4.24 million, the highest in the last 17 years, while Korean companies reported an average loss of approximately KRW 4.1 billion. The most damaging attack vector was business email compromise, followed by social engineering attacks and phishing [<a href="#B10-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">10</a>].</div><section  id='sec3dot1dot1-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h4 class='' data-nested='3'>  3.1.1. Kaseya Incident</h4><div class='html-p'>In July 2021, during the U.S. Independence Day holiday, the IT management platform VSA, provided by Kaseya, an IT management solutions provider, was exploited by the REvil ransomware group as a distribution pathway. This supply chain attack led to ransomware being updated through VSA servers, affecting approximately 200 customer companies, resulting in substantial damage [<a href="#B11-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">11</a>].</div></section><section  id='sec3dot1dot2-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h4 class='' data-nested='3'>  3.1.2. Seoul St. Mary’s Hospital Website Hack</h4><div class='html-p'>In September 2021, the website of Seoul St. Mary’s Hospital, affiliated with the Catholic University of Korea, was hacked, leading to a data breach of members’ personal information. The affected users were those who had registered before February 2013, and the exposed data included user IDs, passwords, and resident registration numbers.</div></section><section  id='sec3dot1dot3-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h4 class='' data-nested='3'>  3.1.3. Cyber Incidents Related to ICS/OT</h4><div class='html-p'>Ransomware, which was primarily recognized as a form of hacking occurring in IT environments, has recently been adopted in OT (Operational Technology) environments as well [<a href="#B12-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">12</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>Moreover, ransomware attacks have evolved beyond merely encrypting data and demanding payment; attackers now infiltrate deeper into internal systems and networks of victim companies, demanding additional ransom payments [<a href="#B13-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">13</a>]. <a href="#applsci-14-11836-t001" class="html-table">Table 1</a> below outlines recent ICS/OT cyber incidents both domestically and internationally [<a href="#B14-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">14</a>].</div></section></section><section  id='sec3dot2-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h3 class='html-italic' data-nested='2'>  3.2. Limitations of Traditional Integrated Security Products and Common Security Vulnerabilities</h3><div class='html-p'>SIEM (Security Information and Event Management) and ESM (Enterprise Security Management) are capable of centrally managing security threat information collected from individual security products [<a href="#B15-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">15</a>]. However, it is challenging to quantitatively assess security incidents on an enterprise-wide scale [<a href="#B16-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">16</a>]. This difficulty is further exacerbated by the heavy reliance on the capabilities of information security personnel, making it hard to assess the increasing likelihood of security incidents. Below, <a href="#applsci-14-11836-t002" class="html-table">Table 2</a> outlines the functions and usage of SIEM and ESM, highlighting their distinctions.</div><div class='html-p'>While <a href="#applsci-14-11836-t002" class="html-table">Table 2</a> outlines the functions and usage of SIEM and ESM, it also highlights their inherent weaknesses, which limit their effectiveness in modern cybersecurity environments.</div><div class='html-p'>One significant limitation of SIEM systems is their heavy reliance on structured data for analysis. As organizations increasingly adopt cloud-based services, IoT devices, and other emerging technologies, the volume of unstructured or semi-structured log data continues to grow. SIEM systems often lack the capability to effectively process and analyze this type of data, resulting in blind spots that can be exploited by sophisticated attackers. Additionally, the dependency on predefined correlation rules and manual input from security personnel further restricts their ability to scale and respond dynamically to evolving threats. This reactive nature makes it challenging to detect novel attack patterns, such as zero-day vulnerabilities or multi-vector threats.</div><div class='html-p'>ESM systems, while designed to centralize security monitoring, share similar limitations. They rely on manual efforts to consolidate and analyze security threat information, which can delay detection and response times. Their focus on real-time monitoring of specific network threats often leads to a narrow scope of analysis, leaving broader attack patterns undetected. Furthermore, ESM systems are constrained by their compatibility with structured log data, which reduces their ability to incorporate diverse data formats generated by modern security infrastructures.</div><div class='html-p'>Both systems face challenges in integrating with legacy platforms, which frequently use proprietary log formats or outdated protocols. This lack of seamless integration hampers the comprehensive visibility required for effective threat management. Moreover, the overwhelming volume of logs and security events processed by these systems often results in high rates of false positives and negatives. This not only burdens security teams but also increases the likelihood of critical threats being overlooked amidst the noise.</div><div class='html-p'>These weaknesses necessitate a paradigm shift in how security incidents are predicted and managed. The traditional reliance on manual processes and reactive methodologies must be replaced with proactive, automated systems capable of handling the complexity and scale of modern cyber threats. By leveraging advancements in artificial intelligence, machine learning, and frameworks such as MITRE ATT&amp;CK, the proposed scenario-based security incident prediction system addresses these challenges directly. This system integrates structured and unstructured data, automates the generation of threat scenarios, and provides context-aware analysis to enhance predictive capabilities and mitigate vulnerabilities effectively [<a href="#B17-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">17</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>By addressing the limitations of SIEM and ESM, this research lays the groundwork for a more robust and adaptive cybersecurity framework that aligns with the demands of increasingly interconnected and complex digital ecosystems.</div></section></section><section  id='sec4-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h2 data-nested='1'>  4. Requirements for Enterprise-Wide Security Incident Prevention</h2><section  id='sec4dot1-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h3 class='html-italic' data-nested='2'>  4.1. Continuous Threat Prediction System</h3><div class='html-p'>To predict security threats, an attack type analysis system based on internal system logs is required. This system must analyze logs from internal systems and filter logs that match attack types and causes received from the cloud system. It should also be able to provide a suspicious activity prediction score based on significant log filtering [<a href="#B18-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">18</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>Additionally, if attack type analysis is performed using logs from user PCs, the system must detect anomalies such as unusual activities in CPU, RAM, or DISK, caused by unauthorized processes [<a href="#B19-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">19</a>].</div><div class='html-p'><a href="#applsci-14-11836-f001" class="html-fig">Figure 1</a> and <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f002" class="html-fig">Figure 2</a> illustrate examples of remote control malware behavior, log-based attack type analysis, and the behavioral process of SDB malware [<a href="#B20-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">20</a>].</div></section><section  id='sec4dot2-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h3 class='html-italic' data-nested='2'>  4.2. Response Measures to Protect the Entire System</h3><div class='html-p'>To integrate with internal security systems, it is necessary to develop a standardized API based on the REST API method that can interface with legacy products such as DRM, firewalls, IDS, and IPS. As the log data format varies across different systems, a new standardized log data format should be defined. When adopting REST communication methods, encrypted communication must be applied to ensure data stability [<a href="#B21-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">21</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>Additionally, for customized corporate services, a structured input system for entering information related to security incidents, including the target and type of incidents, needs to be established as shown in <a href="#applsci-14-11836-t003" class="html-table">Table 3</a>.</div><div class='html-p'>The definitions of internal and external security incident types are shown in <a href="#applsci-14-11836-t004" class="html-table">Table 4</a> below.</div></section></section><section  id='sec5-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h2 data-nested='1'>  5. Limitations of the Reactive Approach to Existing Threats</h2><div class='html-p'>An analysis of existing security incident response methods reveals that traditional approaches predominantly rely on reactive measures that address threats only after they have occurred. These approaches are primarily based on signature-based detection and heuristic techniques, which are inherently limited in predicting and mitigating new or advanced threats [<a href="#B22-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">22</a>]. Consequently, this reactive nature hinders proactive prevention and rapid response, increasing the overall vulnerability of systems to emerging cyberattacks.</div><div class='html-p'>Current security frameworks fail to fully integrate scientific research and proactive strategies, creating structural limitations in predicting and addressing future threats. For example, systems such as Security Information and Event Management (SIEM) and Enterprise Security Management (ESM) focus on collecting and correlating security events and logs within organizations. However, their effectiveness is constrained by heavy reliance on manual analysis by security personnel, which limits scalability and accuracy in forecasting and categorizing potential incidents [<a href="#B23-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">23</a>]. This dependency undermines the ability to analyze advanced threats effectively and hampers timely and systematic responses to novel attack vectors. Integrating advanced threat modeling frameworks, such as the MITRE ATT&amp;CK framework, could address these limitations by enhancing predictive capabilities and streamlining incident response processes.</div><div class='html-p'>As illustrated in <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f003" class="html-fig">Figure 3</a>, the existing proxy-based relay server log collection method highlights inefficiencies in categorizing and processing raw data. Although distributed log collection provides scalability, it lacks the technical capacity to proactively analyze and respond to sophisticated threats using advanced threat intelligence. Furthermore, the current log architecture is inadequate for refining unstructured logs into actionable insights, impeding the detection of new attack vectors and preemptive mitigation of system-wide threats [<a href="#B24-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">24</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>To address these challenges, redefining log data into structured formats suitable for predictive analytics is essential. Adopting scientific methodologies and leveraging artificial intelligence-based tools for real-time data processing and analysis could overcome the current system’s limitations [<a href="#B25-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">25</a>]. Additionally, employing historical data and simulation-based methods to generate threat scenarios would enable organizations to predict attack vectors before they materialize, thereby adopting a forward-looking security posture. Integrating findings from academic and industrial research into practical applications would further strengthen the capability to address sophisticated attacks, bridging the gap between theoretical frameworks and real-world implementations [<a href="#B26-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">26</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>These efforts would transform traditional reactive systems into a comprehensive security framework that combines proactive methodologies, enabling robust defenses against both known and emerging threats. This integration is crucial for achieving a more resilient and adaptive security posture in the face of evolving cyber threats [<a href="#B8-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">8</a>].</div></section><section  id='sec6-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h2 data-nested='1'>  6. The MITRE Corporation ATT&amp;CK Framework Analysis</h2><div class='html-p'>The ATT&amp;CK (Adversary Tactics and Techniques, Common Knowledge) framework was developed through research initiated by the non-profit research and development organization MITRE, which originally started as an entity performing work related to U.S. national security. However, with the rise of cyberattacks and security breaches between nations, additional research was conducted, leading to the creation of the framework [<a href="#B27-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">27</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>The framework provided by ATT&amp;CK consists of a 14-step attack strategy process based on real adversarial activities conducted through networks [<a href="#B28-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">28</a>]. It includes processes that utilize various tactics, techniques, procedures, and attack tools. Understanding the ATT&amp;CK framework requires an understanding of the 14-step strategy process, which is based on the concept of the cyber kill chain [<a href="#B29-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">29</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>The cyber kill chain is one of the most well-known models for analyzing cyberattacks. It originates from military terminology, where the goal is not to intercept a missile after it is launched but to prevent the launch altogether through preemptive action. This concept was adapted to the cyber domain [<a href="#B30-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">30</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>MITRE ATT&amp;CK is an acronym for “Adversarial Tactics, Techniques, and Common Knowledge,” and serves as a repository of the latest attack techniques used by adversaries. After observing real cyberattack cases, the framework analyzes the behaviors of adversaries from the perspective of tactics and techniques, categorizing and listing the various attack methods employed by different attack groups in a standardized data format.</div><div class='html-p'>The MITRE ATT&amp;CK framework visualizes the concepts and relationships between tactics and techniques. Each tactic contains various techniques, and as of April 2021, the ATT&amp;CK Enterprise version provides information on 14 tactics, 185 techniques, and 367 sub-techniques. The ATT&amp;CK matrix information is displayed as shown in <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f004" class="html-fig">Figure 4</a> below.</div><div class='html-p'>MITRE ATT&amp;CK describes 14 strategic stages, and as of January 2023, it categorizes 224 tactics that are used to achieve these strategies. The ATT&amp;CK framework contains a variety of tactics corresponding to each strategy. Over the years, many companies and organizations have adopted this framework, and as the importance of security continues to grow, IT security professionals emphasize the necessity of utilizing it [<a href="#B31-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">31</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>Consequently, more companies, organizations, and even government agencies or specific service communities are adopting the ATT&amp;CK framework to develop threat models and methodologies. In this study, we aim to create rules for detecting tactics corresponding to each strategy based on MITRE ATT&amp;CK, and we will generate scenarios for detecting logs that match suspicious network and data leakage attacks.</div><div class='html-p'>To achieve this, we first analyzed the ATT&amp;CK-based attack tactics and software commonly used by major hacker groups and proceeded to classify the ATT&amp;CK techniques that could be utilized in this research [<a href="#B32-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">32</a>].</div><section  id='sec6dot1-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h3 class='html-italic' data-nested='2'>  6.1. Classification of Attack Types and Feasible Tactics for Attack Simulation</h3><div class='html-p'>The classification of attack types and feasible tactics is essential for simulating realistic attack scenarios and designing effective defensive strategies. Using the MITRE ATT&amp;CK framework, this study categorizes various attack types based on tactics and techniques frequently employed by adversaries. <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f005" class="html-fig">Figure 5</a> and <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f006" class="html-fig">Figure 6</a> illustrate the simulated techniques corresponding to each tactic and provide insights into their feasibility and unique characteristics.</div><div class='html-p'>The classification process began with an analysis of the tactics and techniques documented in the ATT&amp;CK framework, which organizes adversarial behavior into 14 high-level tactics, each encompassing multiple techniques. These techniques were selected based on their relevance to the scenarios explored in this study, as well as their frequency of occurrence in documented cyberattacks. For example, initial access techniques such as phishing and valid account abuse were mapped to scenarios simulating social engineering and insider threats. This mapping provides a structured foundation for understanding the progression of attacks and planning effective countermeasures.</div><div class='html-p'>As depicted in <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f005" class="html-fig">Figure 5</a>, the techniques selected for simulation were evaluated for their feasibility within the context of this study. The evaluation considered factors such as the availability of tools, the complexity of execution, and the potential impact on targeted systems. For instance, the use of credential dumping was deemed both impactful and highly feasible due to its reliance on publicly available tools. Similarly, data exfiltration was analyzed for its adaptability to multiple scenarios, reflecting its versatility as a tactic in real-world breaches [<a href="#B33-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">33</a>].</div><div class='html-p'><a href="#applsci-14-11836-f006" class="html-fig">Figure 6</a> complements this analysis by highlighting specific peculiarities of each technique. For example, the simulation of spear phishing required the incorporation of email spoofing and malicious attachments, while lateral movement scenarios necessitated tools for exploiting weak authentication mechanisms. This detailed breakdown not only demonstrates the adaptability of the selected techniques but also ensures that the simulations align closely with realistic attack patterns.</div><div class='html-p'>The classification framework developed in this section serves as the backbone for the scenario-based simulations conducted in subsequent sections. By aligning the selected techniques with real-world adversarial behaviors, this study ensures that the proposed defense mechanisms are both practical and robust. Furthermore, the integration of the MITRE ATT&amp;CK framework allows for a standardized approach to evaluating the effectiveness of security measures, contributing to the broader applicability of the findings.</div><div class='html-p'>Through this detailed analysis and the visual aids provided in <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f005" class="html-fig">Figure 5</a> and <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f006" class="html-fig">Figure 6</a>, this section establishes a clear and systematic approach to classifying attack types and their corresponding tactics. This comprehensive foundation is critical for designing simulations that accurately reflect the evolving landscape of cybersecurity threats [<a href="#B34-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">34</a>].</div></section><section  id='sec6dot2-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h3 class='html-italic' data-nested='2'>  6.2. Examples of Utilizing MITRE ATT&amp;CK</h3><div class='html-p'>This section presents specific examples of utilizing the MITRE ATT&amp;CK framework to analyze real-world cyber incidents and extract actionable insights. The framework’s standardized structure provides a comprehensive lens through which adversarial behaviors can be understood and categorized, enabling a detailed examination of attack scenarios.</div><div class='html-p'>The examples highlighted in <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f007" class="html-fig">Figure 7</a> and <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f008" class="html-fig">Figure 8</a>, including the Korea Hydro &amp; Nuclear Power hacking incident and the Iranian nuclear power plant attack, were selected based on their relevance to the framework’s 14 tactics. Each attack was systematically analyzed to identify the adversarial techniques employed, such as privilege escalation or data destruction, and to map them onto the corresponding tactics within the ATT&amp;CK matrix. This mapping process revealed patterns in attack progression, illustrating how adversaries exploit specific vulnerabilities to achieve their objectives [<a href="#B35-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">35</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>While <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f007" class="html-fig">Figure 7</a> provides a schematic breakdown of the attack lifecycle in the Korea Hydro &amp; Nuclear Power incident, <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f008" class="html-fig">Figure 8</a> demonstrates similar patterns observed in the Iranian case. The visualizations emphasize the commonalities and differences between these incidents, particularly in their use of lateral movement and defense evasion techniques. This analysis underscores the adaptability of the ATT&amp;CK framework in modeling complex attack scenarios and identifying gaps in existing defenses.</div><div class='html-p'>The insights derived from these analyses were not limited to understanding past incidents but were also used to inform the design of simulated attack scenarios for this study. By leveraging the structured methodology of the ATT&amp;CK framework, these examples serve as templates for constructing realistic scenarios that align with the objectives of proactive threat modeling and defense strategy development.</div><div class='html-p'>This section demonstrates the utility of the ATT&amp;CK framework in bridging theoretical models and practical applications, ensuring that the findings are both relevant to academic research and applicable to real-world cybersecurity challenges. <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f009" class="html-fig">Figure 9</a> compares the attacks between different hacking groups using the navigator function.</div></section></section><section  id='sec7-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h2 data-nested='1'>  7. Proposal for Security Incident Simulation Method</h2><section  id='sec7dot1-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h3 class='html-italic' data-nested='2'>  7.1. Security Incident Profiling Service</h3><div class='html-p'>The profiling service begins by analyzing various types of potential security incidents through the collection and integration of security logs from installed security products. This system quantifies and evaluates the likelihood of each incident type by linking logs with adversarial tactics and techniques derived from the MITRE ATT&amp;CK framework.</div><div class='html-p'>As depicted in <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f010" class="html-fig">Figure 10</a>, the profiling process employs a time-series data collection method combined with network analysis to predict the probability of specific security incidents. The collected logs, both structured and unstructured, are processed and refined for integration into a distributed architecture. <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f011" class="html-fig">Figure 11</a> highlights the use of tools such as Nmap to gather network asset information, which is then analyzed for potential vulnerabilities. <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f012" class="html-fig">Figure 12</a> further details the asset information, including system types and configurations, which are crucial for mapping potential attack surfaces [<a href="#B36-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">36</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>Unlike traditional profiling methods, this study incorporates a structured scenario generation approach that emphasizes adaptability and precision. By utilizing these processes and tools, the system bridges the gap between conventional security monitoring and proactive threat evaluation, enabling organizations to anticipate and mitigate security risks more effectively.</div></section><section  id='sec7dot2-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h3 class='html-italic' data-nested='2'>  7.2. Security Incident Scenario Service</h3><div class='html-p'>This service involves building a system that generates security incident scenarios and enables their prediction and management. The system operates through an engine that determines the likelihood of all types of security incidents at the current time based on both collected and input information within the organization. The process of generating security incident scenarios consists of four steps: data collection, analysis, profiling, and scenario generation. <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f013" class="html-fig">Figure 13</a> below shows an example of classification and determination for different types of security incidents [<a href="#B37-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">37</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>The virtual security incident scenarios are automatically collected and mapped onto the internal system diagram, analyzing each security incident’s vulnerabilities and malware characteristics. This provides a visualized UI depicting the potential flow of actual security incidents. Scenario-based penetration tests are conducted, helping even general administrators easily understand the flow of each security incident [<a href="#B38-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">38</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>Additionally, by incorporating vulnerabilities specific to each endpoint, virtual scenarios like the one shown in <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f014" class="html-fig">Figure 14</a> are generated, offering predictions of potential incidents and suggesting appropriate countermeasures.</div></section><section  id='sec7dot3-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h3 class='html-italic' data-nested='2'>  7.3. Procedure for Threat Analysis and Countermeasure Development</h3><div class='html-p'>PASTA (Process for Attack Simulation and Threat Analysis) is a threat modeling framework developed in 2012. As shown in <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f015" class="html-fig">Figure 15</a>, it consists of seven stages, each involving different activities. This paper focuses on stage 4, which deals with threat analysis, and stage 6, which covers attack modeling.</div><div class='html-p'>Based on the PASTA threat analysis model in <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f016" class="html-fig">Figure 16</a>, as well as the strategies and techniques from the MITRE ATT&amp;CK framework, the threat analysis procedure can be defined as follows.</div><div class='html-p'>Based on the scenario generation procedure, the security incident prediction and management web system should be enhanced to assess the likelihood of various types of security incidents occurring at the present time, using both collected and input information from within the organization. By improving the system to predict and monitor potential future incidents, several key reporting functions are required to facilitate effective response.</div><div class='html-p'>First, the system must enable security incident prediction and monitoring, as well as provide comprehensive reporting capabilities. This includes proposing countermeasures for new types of security incidents through integration with cloud-based systems and identifying the causes and appropriate responses to major security incidents both domestically and internationally [<a href="#B39-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">39</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>Additionally, the system should be capable of generating prediction lists for different incident types, tailored to the specific organizational context. Ensuring the security of collected information through encryption across all communication channels is crucial, along with the implementation of a notification system (such as SMS or email) to help prevent incidents outside regular working hours.</div><div class='html-p'>Furthermore, it is essential to automate the generation of security audit reports. This would involve the automated collection of logs from security products, including SIEM and ESM, ensuring seamless integration with existing security infrastructures.</div><div class='html-p'>A structured classification system for security incident types is also necessary. This classification should be based on industry-specific characteristics—such as finance, healthcare, and manufacturing—while organizing security incidents into broader categories such as external, internal, and supply chain threats. Systematizing incident types like hacking, data leakage, and supply chain tampering would provide a clear framework for incident management.</div><div class='html-p'>Finally, the system should incorporate AI-driven capabilities to predict the likelihood of specific types of security incidents. A comprehensive dashboard and management tools should be provided, enabling administrators to effectively monitor and respond to these predicted incidents [<a href="#B40-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">40</a>].</div></section><section  id='sec7dot4-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h3 class='html-italic' data-nested='2'>  7.4. Legacy Integration and Automated Security Audits</h3><div class='html-p'>To integrate legacy systems and automate security audits, the security incident scenarios should be matched with the tactics provided by the MITRE ATT&amp;CK framework. Scenario-based penetration tests would then be conducted to determine the success rates of various types of security incidents. This process will help identify vulnerable areas and highlight aspects that require improvement. The results of these penetration tests, as well as the corresponding attack scenarios, will be produced as illustrated in <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f017" class="html-fig">Figure 17</a>, <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f018" class="html-fig">Figure 18</a> and <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f019" class="html-fig">Figure 19</a>.</div></section><section  id='sec7dot5-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h3 class='html-italic' data-nested='2'>  7.5. Results of Scenario-Based Simulation Experiments</h3><div class='html-p'>The scenario-based simulation experiments aimed to verify the effectiveness of the proposed profiling and detection system against real-world attack vectors. Four distinct scenarios, including customer data exfiltration, DLL tampering, and malicious program attribute modification, were simulated using tools like Snort, with predefined detection rules applied to analyze network traffic and system behavior [<a href="#B41-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">41</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>As shown in <a href="#applsci-14-11836-t005" class="html-table">Table 5</a>, the Snort rules were tailored to detect specific attack patterns, including packet content and payload characteristics. For instance, the rule alert ip 10.0.0.33 5001 -&gt; any any (msg: “ESE Attack 17”; content: “POST/fileUpload”; nocase; sid:100004;) was used to detect unauthorized file uploads, while another rule targeted DLL tampering by identifying the changeFile command. These customized rules demonstrated the flexibility and precision of the detection system in addressing varied attack scenarios.To evaluate the approach further, the simulation results were compared against traditional methods used in cyber ranges. The proposed system showcased improved detection rates and adaptability to complex attack patterns, particularly in scenarios involving lateral movement and data exfiltration. While these tests were conducted in a controlled environment, future plans include testing in live operational settings to validate scalability and real-time response capabilities, ensuring practical applicability and enhanced security resilience [<a href="#B42-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">42</a>].</div><section  id='sec7dot5dot1-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h4 class='' data-nested='3'>  7.5.1. Custom Attack Simulation 1—Transmitting an Excel File Containing Customer Information from an Internal Agent to an External Destination</h4><div class='html-p'>- Detection Rule for the Packet: alert ip 10.0.0.33 5001 -&gt; any any (msg: “ESE Attack 17”; content: “POST/fileUpload”; nocase; sid:100004;)</div><div class='html-p'>Snort is executed as shown in <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f020" class="html-fig">Figure 20</a> below.</div><div class='html-p'>After executing the customer information leakage attack from the attack scenario list, check the Snort logs shown in <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f021" class="html-fig">Figure 21</a>, <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f022" class="html-fig">Figure 22</a> and <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f023" class="html-fig">Figure 23</a> below. It shows the security incident scenario.</div><div class='html-p'>In the log, you can see that the S1I005_private.xlsx file was uploaded to 10.0.0.44:8091 using the HTTP POST method.</div></section><section  id='sec7dot5dot2-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h4 class='' data-nested='3'>  7.5.2. Custom Attack Simulation 2—Internal DLL File Tampering</h4><div class='html-p'>- Detection Rule for the Packet: alert ip any any -&gt; 10.0.0.33 5001 (msg: “ESE Attack 2”; content: “changeFile”; nocase; sid:100003;)</div><div class='html-p'>After executing the internal DLL file tampering attack from the attack scenario list as shown in <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f024" class="html-fig">Figure 24</a>, check the Snort logs in <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f025" class="html-fig">Figure 25</a>. Next up is It shows the security incident scenario.</div><div class='html-p'>Upon reviewing the log, it can be confirmed that the S0E002_origin.dll file was renamed to SoE002_execute.dll using the ChangeFile command. Although a test file name was used, the simulation results show that tampering with files within the C:\Windows\System32 folder is also possible.</div></section><section  id='sec7dot5dot3-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h4 class='' data-nested='3'>  7.5.3. Custom Attack Simulation 3—Setting a Malicious Program File as a Hidden File</h4><div class='html-p'>- Detection Rule for the Packet: alert ip any any -&gt; 10.0.0.33 5001 (msg: “ESE Attack 5”; content: “changeFileAttributes”; nocase; sid:100005;)</div><div class='html-p'>After executing the internal network hacking scenario from the attack scenario list as shown in <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f026" class="html-fig">Figure 26</a>, check the Snort logs in <a href="#applsci-14-11836-f027" class="html-fig">Figure 27</a>. Next up is It shows the security incident scenario.</div><div class='html-p'>The log confirms that the attacker successfully deleted the targeted file. Although a test file name was used, the simulation results indicate that files within the C:\Windows\System32 folder can also be targeted for system destruction using the same method.</div></section></section></section><section  id='sec8-applsci-14-11836' type=''><h2 data-nested='1'>  8. Evaluation</h2><div class='html-p'>The proposed system was evaluated in a virtualized environment designed to replicate a typical enterprise network. The environment included a centralized logging system, a Security Information and Event Management (SIEM) system, and various legacy security systems, such as firewalls and Intrusion Detection Systems (IDS). These components were configured to generate and collect security logs, which served as the primary input for testing the system’s ability to predict and respond to security incidents.</div><div class='html-p'>To assess the effectiveness of the proposed system, attack traffic was simulated using scenarios based on the MITRE ATT&amp;CK framework. The simulation focused on replicating common attack vectors, including credential dumping, data exfiltration, and phishing attacks. These scenarios were selected to reflect real-world adversarial behaviors and were implemented using network traffic generation tools such as Snort. The generated traffic logs were then analyzed to determine whether the system could identify patterns associated with the simulated attacks. This approach allowed for a comprehensive evaluation of the system’s capacity to detect and mitigate potential threats in a realistic operational setting.</div><div class='html-p'>The dataset used for evaluation consisted of a combination of real-time logs generated within the experimental environment and data collected through network asset scanning using Nmap. While publicly available datasets such as CICIDS2017 or KDD Cup 99 were not employed, the internal log data provided a sufficiently diverse and representative sample of potential attack scenarios. Future iterations of this study aim to incorporate publicly available datasets to enable broader benchmarking and validation of the system’s performance.</div><div class='html-p'>The evaluation demonstrated the proposed system’s ability to effectively identify and analyze security incidents under simulated conditions. However, additional testing in live operational environments and with a wider range of datasets will be necessary to further validate its scalability and adaptability to evolving cyber threats.</div></section><section  id='sec9-applsci-14-11836' type='conclusions'><h2 data-nested='1'>  9. Conclusions</h2><div class='html-p'>As security technologies continue to evolve, so too do the methods employed by attackers, who exploit various environments and routes to bypass traditional defense mechanisms. This study highlights the importance of understanding attack techniques and processes through scenario-based simulations, which offer a structured approach to predicting and mitigating potential security incidents. By analyzing vulnerabilities specific to different system configurations and integrating the characteristics of malware, this study proposes a method for generating virtual security scenarios that enable organizations to respond proactively to emerging threats [<a href="#B43-applsci-14-11836" class="html-bibr">43</a>].</div><div class='html-p'>While the proposed methodology provides a comprehensive framework for incident prediction and response, there are areas that warrant further exploration. Future work will focus on testing the proposed system in live operational environments to assess its scalability and real-time detection capabilities. Additionally, enhancing the system’s ability to integrate with diverse legacy systems and refining its AI-driven analytics for more precise threat predictions will be critical. Expanding the scope of simulated scenarios to include more sophisticated attack vectors, such as supply chain attacks and AI-driven threats, will also be an area of emphasis.</div><div class='html-p'>By addressing these areas in future research, the proposed framework can be further refined to offer more robust and adaptive solutions, ensuring a higher level of resilience against evolving cyber threats.</div></section>
  </div>
